text: I have a prediction, but I might be majorly wrong. Here it is: I think her killer is her father. Why? First of all, when her father called her that morning, he seemed pretty urgent to since he called her in the morning. Something could've been wrong with him or he was going crazy, which would later cause him to kill his own daughter. Secondly, as you can see during her first death, the killer seems to be much taller than her, which also may imply it's her father. Also, her friend said that the killer would know it was her birthday. Her father should have an idea of when she was born, right? And also, when she told that girl someone was going to. "Kill her tonight" she hid at home, and the person most likely to know where she lives is her father. The mother was never seen in any of this and the same goes for her dad. Also, not trying to be sexist or anything, the person that DID kill her seemed to have a manly figure, which also maybe shows my point. I know this could be wrong, but it's just my prediction.

text: It seems like there isn't any real tension. Yeah, there is a person trying to kill you, and you are constantly dying and reliving the same day, but... The guy seriously says "You have unlimited lives", so how is it supposed to be tense when the killer is chasing her? You end up thinking "Oh well, who cares she will just wake up and get another chance to do this, over and over again." Plus, this means she can get away with all kinds of shit and basically do whatever she wants until tonight, then let the person kill her to erase the evidence.  So, how is this a bad thing? It never says "You only get a certain amount of times to do this" and her day doesn't seem to be that bad up until she gets killed.

text: I have come here to complain against this annoyance that is called 'happy death day'. I have received endless trailers for the movie for nearly a month now and am sick of it. The trailers have once again delivered essentially the entire plot in a mere fifteen second interval, leaving only the "burning" solution to this white-chicks predicament to be unraveled. Tell me, if you put a cover over a horses head but leave its body exposed, you can still clearly envision what the head looks like because of your previous familiarity with the physical form of the mammal, correct? The movie is uncreative, cringingly-comical, and not in any way frightening in the least bit. The main character is a chunga, the use of 50 cents in the club kills any mood of forbiddance, and the killer isn't profound or terrifying in any way. It looks retarded in that stupid baby mask. Its like someone took Ground-Hog Day, a poorly done mixtape, and Scream 4, shoved them into a blender, pissed in it, and dumped the remnants onto Michael Bays scrawny little lap for him to fondle with. I cant even tell if its supposed to be an actual slasher film, because it seems even more absurd than a more recent horror comedy (Get Out), minus the intentionality that is. And that's not the scary part. Its the audience willingness to pay money for the corporate regurgitations that's disheartening to the very soul. We are like blind dogs eating our own cinematic vomit.  I hope from the bottom of my cavity of a heart that this movie does awful at the box office.

text: Ok, the answer of this question is related to a ghosty matter. This day has been given to her as a gift of her mother. You saw the doll that was sitting on the road; her Mother showed this to her. Her mother knew that she would die on the day that is before her birthday; so she showed her this doll just before her death. Yes, she didn't die on her birthday and died on the day that is one day before her birthday. Her mother wanted to give her the remaining part of her life as the gift of her birthday that was tomorrow; this is why she have her go through this time loop so that she can live for more time by saving herself from this killer and can live for more days happily. Her mother showed this to her just before her death to comprehend this to her that gaining this will not be easy.
